</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Solid and cystic pancreatic neoplasms are being recognized more frequently with increasing utilization and spatial resolution of modern imaging techniques. In addition to the more common primary pancreatic solid (ductal adenocarcinoma) and cystic neoplasms of epithelial origin, nonepithelial neoplasms of the pancreas may appear as well-defined solid or cystic neoplasms. Most of these lesions have characteristic imaging features, such as a well-defined border, which allows differentiation from ductal adenocarcinoma. Solid masses include neurofibroma, ganglioneuroma, leiomyoma, lipoma, and perivascular epithelioid cell tumor (PEComa). Schwannomas and desmoid tumors can be solid or cystic. Cystic tumors include mature cystic teratoma and lymphangioma. Lipoma, PEComa, and mature cystic teratoma can contain fat, and ganglioneuroma and mature cystic teratoma may contain calcification. Although these unusual benign neoplasms are rare, the radiologist should at least consider them in the differential diagnosis of well-defined lesions of the pancreas. The goal of this comprehensive review is to improve understanding of these rare primary pancreatic mesenchymal tumors.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150212">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150212">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig1a.jpeg" height="810" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Neurofibroma in a 26-year-old woman with a 2-month history of vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows an encapsulated, firm, white, shiny mass within the head of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows small ovoid to spindled cells with dark nuclei (arrow) in a background of myxoid/collagenous matrix (*). (Original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a multilobulated soft-tissue mass with variable echogenicity: to the right, there is a “target” appearance with central hyperechogenicity (*) and a peripheral hypoechoic rim (straight arrow); to the left, the mass is more homogeneously hypoechoic (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Color Doppler image shows the well-defined solid mass arising from the pancreatic neck, with internal vascularity within the target portion (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mild enhancement of the well-defined homogeneously hypoattenuating solid mass (arrow) arising from the head/neck of the pancreas, without upstream pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig1b.jpeg" height="810" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Neurofibroma in a 26-year-old woman with a 2-month history of vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows an encapsulated, firm, white, shiny mass within the head of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows small ovoid to spindled cells with dark nuclei (arrow) in a background of myxoid/collagenous matrix (*). (Original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a multilobulated soft-tissue mass with variable echogenicity: to the right, there is a “target” appearance with central hyperechogenicity (*) and a peripheral hypoechoic rim (straight arrow); to the left, the mass is more homogeneously hypoechoic (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Color Doppler image shows the well-defined solid mass arising from the pancreatic neck, with internal vascularity within the target portion (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mild enhancement of the well-defined homogeneously hypoattenuating solid mass (arrow) arising from the head/neck of the pancreas, without upstream pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig1c.jpeg" height="786" width="915" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Neurofibroma in a 26-year-old woman with a 2-month history of vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows an encapsulated, firm, white, shiny mass within the head of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows small ovoid to spindled cells with dark nuclei (arrow) in a background of myxoid/collagenous matrix (*). (Original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a multilobulated soft-tissue mass with variable echogenicity: to the right, there is a “target” appearance with central hyperechogenicity (*) and a peripheral hypoechoic rim (straight arrow); to the left, the mass is more homogeneously hypoechoic (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Color Doppler image shows the well-defined solid mass arising from the pancreatic neck, with internal vascularity within the target portion (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mild enhancement of the well-defined homogeneously hypoattenuating solid mass (arrow) arising from the head/neck of the pancreas, without upstream pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig1d.jpeg" height="787" width="960" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Neurofibroma in a 26-year-old woman with a 2-month history of vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows an encapsulated, firm, white, shiny mass within the head of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows small ovoid to spindled cells with dark nuclei (arrow) in a background of myxoid/collagenous matrix (*). (Original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a multilobulated soft-tissue mass with variable echogenicity: to the right, there is a “target” appearance with central hyperechogenicity (*) and a peripheral hypoechoic rim (straight arrow); to the left, the mass is more homogeneously hypoechoic (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Color Doppler image shows the well-defined solid mass arising from the pancreatic neck, with internal vascularity within the target portion (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mild enhancement of the well-defined homogeneously hypoattenuating solid mass (arrow) arising from the head/neck of the pancreas, without upstream pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig1e.jpeg" height="707" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Neurofibroma in a 26-year-old woman with a 2-month history of vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows an encapsulated, firm, white, shiny mass within the head of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows small ovoid to spindled cells with dark nuclei (arrow) in a background of myxoid/collagenous matrix (*). (Original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a multilobulated soft-tissue mass with variable echogenicity: to the right, there is a “target” appearance with central hyperechogenicity (*) and a peripheral hypoechoic rim (straight arrow); to the left, the mass is more homogeneously hypoechoic (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Color Doppler image shows the well-defined solid mass arising from the pancreatic neck, with internal vascularity within the target portion (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mild enhancement of the well-defined homogeneously hypoattenuating solid mass (arrow) arising from the head/neck of the pancreas, without upstream pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig2a.jpeg" height="678" width="773" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Antoni A–predominant schwannoma in a 37-year-old man with upper abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed, encapsulated, pale tan mass (straight arrow) within the body of the pancreas. Note the areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows the thin capsule (straight arrow) surrounding the lobulated tumor embedded in the pancreas. Focal hemorrhage (curved arrow) is seen. (Original magnification, ×2; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig2b.jpeg" height="678" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Antoni A–predominant schwannoma in a 37-year-old man with upper abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed, encapsulated, pale tan mass (straight arrow) within the body of the pancreas. Note the areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows the thin capsule (straight arrow) surrounding the lobulated tumor embedded in the pancreas. Focal hemorrhage (curved arrow) is seen. (Original magnification, ×2; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig3a.jpeg" height="687" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Antoni B–predominant schwannoma in a 36-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed brown-tan solid mass (straight arrow) with loculated cystic components (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows an encapsulated tumor showing various growth patterns: more cellular Antoni A areas with numerous palisading Verocay bodies (straight arrow) and looser Antoni B areas (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig3b.jpeg" height="687" width="911" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Antoni B–predominant schwannoma in a 36-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed brown-tan solid mass (straight arrow) with loculated cystic components (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows an encapsulated tumor showing various growth patterns: more cellular Antoni A areas with numerous palisading Verocay bodies (straight arrow) and looser Antoni B areas (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig4a.jpeg" height="669" width="862" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Antoni A–predominant schwannoma in a 74-year-old man with a 2-week history of right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a small, well-defined, hypoechoic mass (cursors) within the body of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced image obtained during the portal venous phase shows the mass to be relatively hypoattenuating and minimally expansile (arrow). <b>(c)</b> More delayed phase image shows progressive enhancement of the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig4b.jpeg" height="668" width="812" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Antoni A–predominant schwannoma in a 74-year-old man with a 2-week history of right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a small, well-defined, hypoechoic mass (cursors) within the body of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced image obtained during the portal venous phase shows the mass to be relatively hypoattenuating and minimally expansile (arrow). <b>(c)</b> More delayed phase image shows progressive enhancement of the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig4c.jpeg" height="659" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Antoni A–predominant schwannoma in a 74-year-old man with a 2-week history of right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a small, well-defined, hypoechoic mass (cursors) within the body of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced image obtained during the portal venous phase shows the mass to be relatively hypoattenuating and minimally expansile (arrow). <b>(c)</b> More delayed phase image shows progressive enhancement of the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig5a.jpeg" height="733" width="517" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Ganglioneuroma incidentally discovered within the tail of the pancreas in an asymptomatic 28-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a lobulated, relatively homogeneous, white-yellow solid mass with linear bands. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows scattered mature ganglion cells with abundant cytoplasm, round contour, and large nuclei (straight arrow) surrounded by myxoid stroma consisting of thin wavy Schwann cells (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×4; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig5b.jpeg" height="733" width="810" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Ganglioneuroma incidentally discovered within the tail of the pancreas in an asymptomatic 28-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a lobulated, relatively homogeneous, white-yellow solid mass with linear bands. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows scattered mature ganglion cells with abundant cytoplasm, round contour, and large nuclei (straight arrow) surrounded by myxoid stroma consisting of thin wavy Schwann cells (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×4; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig6a.jpeg" height="758" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Ganglioneuroma in a 12-year-old boy with a 2-day history of right upper quadrant pain, lethargy, and anorexia. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images show a large, well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneously hypoechoic ovoid mass (straight arrow) with punctate echogenic foci consistent with calcifications (curved arrow) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a well-circumscribed lobulated hyperintense mass in the pancreatic head, displacing the adjacent liver. Note the curvilinear hypointense band (arrow), which correlates pathologically with collagen fibers. <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image before contrast material administration shows homogeneous low signal intensity within the large solid ovoid mass (arrow) in the expected location of the pancreatic head, exerting mass effect on the caudate lobe of the liver. <b>(e, f)</b> Images obtained after contrast material administration during the portal venous <b>(e)</b> and blood pool <b>(f)</b> phases show mild progressive enhancement as the myxoid stroma accumulates contrast material over time (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig6b.jpeg" height="758" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Ganglioneuroma in a 12-year-old boy with a 2-day history of right upper quadrant pain, lethargy, and anorexia. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images show a large, well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneously hypoechoic ovoid mass (straight arrow) with punctate echogenic foci consistent with calcifications (curved arrow) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a well-circumscribed lobulated hyperintense mass in the pancreatic head, displacing the adjacent liver. Note the curvilinear hypointense band (arrow), which correlates pathologically with collagen fibers. <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image before contrast material administration shows homogeneous low signal intensity within the large solid ovoid mass (arrow) in the expected location of the pancreatic head, exerting mass effect on the caudate lobe of the liver. <b>(e, f)</b> Images obtained after contrast material administration during the portal venous <b>(e)</b> and blood pool <b>(f)</b> phases show mild progressive enhancement as the myxoid stroma accumulates contrast material over time (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig6c.jpeg" height="758" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Ganglioneuroma in a 12-year-old boy with a 2-day history of right upper quadrant pain, lethargy, and anorexia. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images show a large, well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneously hypoechoic ovoid mass (straight arrow) with punctate echogenic foci consistent with calcifications (curved arrow) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a well-circumscribed lobulated hyperintense mass in the pancreatic head, displacing the adjacent liver. Note the curvilinear hypointense band (arrow), which correlates pathologically with collagen fibers. <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image before contrast material administration shows homogeneous low signal intensity within the large solid ovoid mass (arrow) in the expected location of the pancreatic head, exerting mass effect on the caudate lobe of the liver. <b>(e, f)</b> Images obtained after contrast material administration during the portal venous <b>(e)</b> and blood pool <b>(f)</b> phases show mild progressive enhancement as the myxoid stroma accumulates contrast material over time (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig6d.jpeg" height="758" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Ganglioneuroma in a 12-year-old boy with a 2-day history of right upper quadrant pain, lethargy, and anorexia. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images show a large, well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneously hypoechoic ovoid mass (straight arrow) with punctate echogenic foci consistent with calcifications (curved arrow) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a well-circumscribed lobulated hyperintense mass in the pancreatic head, displacing the adjacent liver. Note the curvilinear hypointense band (arrow), which correlates pathologically with collagen fibers. <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image before contrast material administration shows homogeneous low signal intensity within the large solid ovoid mass (arrow) in the expected location of the pancreatic head, exerting mass effect on the caudate lobe of the liver. <b>(e, f)</b> Images obtained after contrast material administration during the portal venous <b>(e)</b> and blood pool <b>(f)</b> phases show mild progressive enhancement as the myxoid stroma accumulates contrast material over time (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig6e.jpeg" height="758" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6e</span>. Ganglioneuroma in a 12-year-old boy with a 2-day history of right upper quadrant pain, lethargy, and anorexia. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images show a large, well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneously hypoechoic ovoid mass (straight arrow) with punctate echogenic foci consistent with calcifications (curved arrow) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a well-circumscribed lobulated hyperintense mass in the pancreatic head, displacing the adjacent liver. Note the curvilinear hypointense band (arrow), which correlates pathologically with collagen fibers. <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image before contrast material administration shows homogeneous low signal intensity within the large solid ovoid mass (arrow) in the expected location of the pancreatic head, exerting mass effect on the caudate lobe of the liver. <b>(e, f)</b> Images obtained after contrast material administration during the portal venous <b>(e)</b> and blood pool <b>(f)</b> phases show mild progressive enhancement as the myxoid stroma accumulates contrast material over time (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig6e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig6f.jpeg" height="758" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6f</span>. Ganglioneuroma in a 12-year-old boy with a 2-day history of right upper quadrant pain, lethargy, and anorexia. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images show a large, well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneously hypoechoic ovoid mass (straight arrow) with punctate echogenic foci consistent with calcifications (curved arrow) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a well-circumscribed lobulated hyperintense mass in the pancreatic head, displacing the adjacent liver. Note the curvilinear hypointense band (arrow), which correlates pathologically with collagen fibers. <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image before contrast material administration shows homogeneous low signal intensity within the large solid ovoid mass (arrow) in the expected location of the pancreatic head, exerting mass effect on the caudate lobe of the liver. <b>(e, f)</b> Images obtained after contrast material administration during the portal venous <b>(e)</b> and blood pool <b>(f)</b> phases show mild progressive enhancement as the myxoid stroma accumulates contrast material over time (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig6f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7a.jpeg" height="605" width="560" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7b.jpeg" height="605" width="638" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7c.jpeg" height="605" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7d.jpeg" height="638" width="607" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7e.jpeg" height="638" width="608" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7f.jpeg" height="636" width="633" aria-labelledby="fig7f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7f</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig7g.jpeg" height="680" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig7g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7g</span>. Parapancreatic ganglioneuroma. <b>(a)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows a well-defined, ovoid, solid-appearing mass that is hypoattenuating to muscle (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images obtained during the arterial <b>(b)</b> and portal venous <b>(c)</b> phases show mild heterogeneous early arterial enhancement that progressively intensifies in the delayed phase (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MR imaging was performed to better characterize the lesion (arrow), which shows low signal intensity on a T1-weighted image <b>(d)</b> and heterogeneous high signal intensity (with respect to muscle) on a T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. <b>(f, g)</b> After contrast material administration, there is minimal arterial phase enhancement <b>(f)</b> with progressive enhancement in the blood pool phase <b>(g)</b> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig7g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig8a.jpeg" height="802" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Fibromatosis in a 32-year-old woman with a 1-month history of left-sided abdominal pain and a palpable left upper quadrant mass. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a large, well-marginated, firm, white, homogeneous solid mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (*). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the tumor to be composed of relatively uniform bland spindle cells. The invasive nature of this lesion is demonstrated by the entrapped Langerhans island (*).(Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and longitudinal Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show a well-defined homogeneous hypoechoic mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) arising from the tail of the pancreas, with internal vascularity (arrow in <b>d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the entire well-defined mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (arrow) with homogeneous mild enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig8b.jpeg" height="802" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Fibromatosis in a 32-year-old woman with a 1-month history of left-sided abdominal pain and a palpable left upper quadrant mass. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a large, well-marginated, firm, white, homogeneous solid mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (*). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the tumor to be composed of relatively uniform bland spindle cells. The invasive nature of this lesion is demonstrated by the entrapped Langerhans island (*).(Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and longitudinal Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show a well-defined homogeneous hypoechoic mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) arising from the tail of the pancreas, with internal vascularity (arrow in <b>d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the entire well-defined mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (arrow) with homogeneous mild enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img 