tively uniform bland spindle cells. The invasive nature of this lesion is demonstrated by the entrapped Langerhans island (*).(Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and longitudinal Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show a well-defined homogeneous hypoechoic mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) arising from the tail of the pancreas, with internal vascularity (arrow in <b>d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the entire well-defined mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (arrow) with homogeneous mild enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig8e.jpeg" height="724" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. Fibromatosis in a 32-year-old woman with a 1-month history of left-sided abdominal pain and a palpable left upper quadrant mass. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a large, well-marginated, firm, white, homogeneous solid mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (*). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the tumor to be composed of relatively uniform bland spindle cells. The invasive nature of this lesion is demonstrated by the entrapped Langerhans island (*).(Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Transverse gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and longitudinal Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show a well-defined homogeneous hypoechoic mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) arising from the tail of the pancreas, with internal vascularity (arrow in <b>d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the entire well-defined mass arising from the tail of the pancreas (arrow) with homogeneous mild enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig9a.jpeg" height="884" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Fibromatosis in an asymptomatic 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a white-tan stellate infiltrative mass (straight arrow) arising from the tail of the pancreas (*) and invading the splenic capsule (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (arrow) between the pancreatic tail and splenic hilum; however, the infiltrative margins are not as well seen in the coronal plane. <b>(c–e)</b> The infiltrative margins of the mass (arrow) are best seen on an axial T2-weighted MR image <b>(c)</b> and T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images before <b>(d)</b> and after <b>(e)</b> contrast material administration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig9b.jpeg" height="667" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Fibromatosis in an asymptomatic 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a white-tan stellate infiltrative mass (straight arrow) arising from the tail of the pancreas (*) and invading the splenic capsule (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (arrow) between the pancreatic tail and splenic hilum; however, the infiltrative margins are not as well seen in the coronal plane. <b>(c–e)</b> The infiltrative margins of the mass (arrow) are best seen on an axial T2-weighted MR image <b>(c)</b> and T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images before <b>(d)</b> and after <b>(e)</b> contrast material administration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig9c.jpeg" height="667" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Fibromatosis in an asymptomatic 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a white-tan stellate infiltrative mass (straight arrow) arising from the tail of the pancreas (*) and invading the splenic capsule (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (arrow) between the pancreatic tail and splenic hilum; however, the infiltrative margins are not as well seen in the coronal plane. <b>(c–e)</b> The infiltrative margins of the mass (arrow) are best seen on an axial T2-weighted MR image <b>(c)</b> and T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images before <b>(d)</b> and after <b>(e)</b> contrast material administration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig9d.jpeg" height="669" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Fibromatosis in an asymptomatic 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a white-tan stellate infiltrative mass (straight arrow) arising from the tail of the pancreas (*) and invading the splenic capsule (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (arrow) between the pancreatic tail and splenic hilum; however, the infiltrative margins are not as well seen in the coronal plane. <b>(c–e)</b> The infiltrative margins of the mass (arrow) are best seen on an axial T2-weighted MR image <b>(c)</b> and T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images before <b>(d)</b> and after <b>(e)</b> contrast material administration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig9e.jpeg" height="669" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Fibromatosis in an asymptomatic 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a white-tan stellate infiltrative mass (straight arrow) arising from the tail of the pancreas (*) and invading the splenic capsule (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (arrow) between the pancreatic tail and splenic hilum; however, the infiltrative margins are not as well seen in the coronal plane. <b>(c–e)</b> The infiltrative margins of the mass (arrow) are best seen on an axial T2-weighted MR image <b>(c)</b> and T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images before <b>(d)</b> and after <b>(e)</b> contrast material administration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig10.jpeg" height="633" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Leiomyoma in a 52-year-old woman with right back/flank pain. Axial CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows a well-marginated homogeneously hypoenhancing mass (arrow) within the distal body of the pancreas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig11a.jpeg" height="774" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Lipoma in a 69-year-old woman with a 1-year history of increased flatulence. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-defined, encapsulated, yellow lobulated mass with a greasy surface. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows a thin capsule (arrow) surrounding the tumor composed of mature adipose cells (*). (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the circumscribed fat-attenuation mass replacing the body of the pancreas (arrow), with mass effect on the distal stomach. * = partially visualized pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig11b.jpeg" height="667" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Lipoma in a 69-year-old woman with a 1-year history of increased flatulence. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-defined, encapsulated, yellow lobulated mass with a greasy surface. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows a thin capsule (arrow) surrounding the tumor composed of mature adipose cells (*). (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the circumscribed fat-attenuation mass replacing the body of the pancreas (arrow), with mass effect on the distal stomach. * = partially visualized pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig11c.jpeg" height="667" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Lipoma in a 69-year-old woman with a 1-year history of increased flatulence. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-defined, encapsulated, yellow lobulated mass with a greasy surface. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows a thin capsule (arrow) surrounding the tumor composed of mature adipose cells (*). (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the circumscribed fat-attenuation mass replacing the body of the pancreas (arrow), with mass effect on the distal stomach. * = partially visualized pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig12a.jpeg" height="724" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Hemorrhagic <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in a 74-year-old woman with diffuse abdominal pain and right upper quadrant tenderness. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a circumscribed mass (straight arrow) within the head of the pancreas (*) with central areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the perivascular storiform growth of epithelioid cells (closest to lumen) and spindle cells (remote from vessel) radially arranged around an artery (arrow). (Original magnification, ×20; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image through the midline upper abdomen shows a well-defined heterogeneous mass (arrow) arising from the head of the pancreas with mixed echogenicity centrally, corresponding to areas of hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows the hemorrhagic component as central hyperattenuation (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-marginated tumor in the head of the pancreas (arrow) with peripheral low attenuation and central hyperattenuation compatible with hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig12b.jpeg" height="669" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Hemorrhagic <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in a 74-year-old woman with diffuse abdominal pain and right upper quadrant tenderness. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a circumscribed mass (straight arrow) within the head of the pancreas (*) with central areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the perivascular storiform growth of epithelioid cells (closest to lumen) and spindle cells (remote from vessel) radially arranged around an artery (arrow). (Original magnification, ×20; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image through the midline upper abdomen shows a well-defined heterogeneous mass (arrow) arising from the head of the pancreas with mixed echogenicity centrally, corresponding to areas of hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows the hemorrhagic component as central hyperattenuation (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-marginated tumor in the head of the pancreas (arrow) with peripheral low attenuation and central hyperattenuation compatible with hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig12c.jpeg" height="668" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Hemorrhagic <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in a 74-year-old woman with diffuse abdominal pain and right upper quadrant tenderness. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a circumscribed mass (straight arrow) within the head of the pancreas (*) with central areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the perivascular storiform growth of epithelioid cells (closest to lumen) and spindle cells (remote from vessel) radially arranged around an artery (arrow). (Original magnification, ×20; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image through the midline upper abdomen shows a well-defined heterogeneous mass (arrow) arising from the head of the pancreas with mixed echogenicity centrally, corresponding to areas of hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows the hemorrhagic component as central hyperattenuation (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-marginated tumor in the head of the pancreas (arrow) with peripheral low attenuation and central hyperattenuation compatible with hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig12d.jpeg" height="666" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span>. Hemorrhagic <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in a 74-year-old woman with diffuse abdominal pain and right upper quadrant tenderness. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a circumscribed mass (straight arrow) within the head of the pancreas (*) with central areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the perivascular storiform growth of epithelioid cells (closest to lumen) and spindle cells (remote from vessel) radially arranged around an artery (arrow). (Original magnification, ×20; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image through the midline upper abdomen shows a well-defined heterogeneous mass (arrow) arising from the head of the pancreas with mixed echogenicity centrally, corresponding to areas of hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows the hemorrhagic component as central hyperattenuation (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-marginated tumor in the head of the pancreas (arrow) with peripheral low attenuation and central hyperattenuation compatible with hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig12e.jpeg" height="667" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig12e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12e</span>. Hemorrhagic <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in a 74-year-old woman with diffuse abdominal pain and right upper quadrant tenderness. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a circumscribed mass (straight arrow) within the head of the pancreas (*) with central areas of hemorrhage (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the perivascular storiform growth of epithelioid cells (closest to lumen) and spindle cells (remote from vessel) radially arranged around an artery (arrow). (Original magnification, ×20; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image through the midline upper abdomen shows a well-defined heterogeneous mass (arrow) arising from the head of the pancreas with mixed echogenicity centrally, corresponding to areas of hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Nonenhanced CT image shows the hemorrhagic component as central hyperattenuation (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-marginated tumor in the head of the pancreas (arrow) with peripheral low attenuation and central hyperattenuation compatible with hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig12e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig13a.jpeg" height="629" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Variable CT appearance of <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows a homogeneously enhancing oval mass (arrow) within the tail of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows a well-defined centrally hypoenhancing mass with peripheral capsular enhancement (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows arterial hyperenhancement of a well-defined <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig13b.jpeg" height="629" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Variable CT appearance of <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows a homogeneously enhancing oval mass (arrow) within the tail of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows a well-defined centrally hypoenhancing mass with peripheral capsular enhancement (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows arterial hyperenhancement of a well-defined <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig13c.jpeg" height="629" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Variable CT appearance of <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows a homogeneously enhancing oval mass (arrow) within the tail of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows a well-defined centrally hypoenhancing mass with peripheral capsular enhancement (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows arterial hyperenhancement of a well-defined <abbr title="perivascular epithelioid cell tumor">PEComa</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig14a.jpeg" height="633" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Mature cystic teratoma in a 3-year-old girl with a clinically palpable right upper quadrant abdominal mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows a mixed-attenuation mass with both macroscopic fat (arrow) and soft-tissue attenuation (*) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a sectioned gross specimen from another patient shows a well-defined cystic mass containing keratin (curved arrow) and fat (straight arrow) within the pancreas (*). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the same specimen shows that the cyst wall is lined by respiratory epithelium (straight arrow) and contains elements of cartilage (*), smooth muscle, adipose tissue, and neural (brain) tissue (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×4; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig14b.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Mature cystic teratoma in a 3-year-old girl with a clinically palpable right upper quadrant abdominal mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows a mixed-attenuation mass with both macroscopic fat (arrow) and soft-tissue attenuation (*) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a sectioned gross specimen from another patient shows a well-defined cystic mass containing keratin (curved arrow) and fat (straight arrow) within the pancreas (*). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the same specimen shows that the cyst wall is lined by respiratory epithelium (straight arrow) and contains elements of cartilage (*), smooth muscle, adipose tissue, and neural (brain) tissue (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×4; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig14c.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Mature cystic teratoma in a 3-year-old girl with a clinically palpable right upper quadrant abdominal mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows a mixed-attenuation mass with both macroscopic fat (arrow) and soft-tissue attenuation (*) in the region of the pancreatic head. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a sectioned gross specimen from another patient shows a well-defined cystic mass containing keratin (curved arrow) and fat (straight arrow) within the pancreas (*). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the same specimen shows that the cyst wall is lined by respiratory epithelium (straight arrow) and contains elements of cartilage (*), smooth muscle, adipose tissue, and neural (brain) tissue (curved arrow). (Original magnification, ×4; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig15a.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Lymphangioma in a 31-year-old man with sudden onset of left upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a multilocular cystic mass with smooth outer and inner surfaces and multiple smooth tan-white internal septa (*). The cysts are filled with clear yellowish fluid and yellow debris (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the tumor is composed of multiple cysts containing thin eosinophilic fluid (*). The cysts are lined by endothelial cells, and the cyst walls contain small accumulations of lymphocytes. Normal pancreatic tissue is seen in the lower right corner <i>(P)</i>. (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and color Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show different areas of a multilocular cystic mass without internal vascularity in the region of the pancreatic body (*). <b>(e, f)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b> and coronal oblique maximum intensity projection reconstructed image created from postcontrast T1-weighted fat-suppressed images obtained during the portal venous phase <b>(f)</b> show the multiloculated macrocystic mass arising from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body (straight arrow). The thin septa (curved arrow) are well seen on the T2-weighted image and show mild enhancement on the postcontrast image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig15b.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Lymphangioma in a 31-year-old man with sudden onset of left upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a multilocular cystic mass with smooth outer and inner surfaces and multiple smooth tan-white internal septa (*). The cysts are filled with clear yellowish fluid and yellow debris (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the tumor is composed of multiple cysts containing thin eosinophilic fluid (*). The cysts are lined by endothelial cells, and the cyst walls contain small accumulations of lymphocytes. Normal pancreatic tissue is seen in the lower right corner <i>(P)</i>. (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and color Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show different areas of a multilocular cystic mass without internal vascularity in the region of the pancreatic body (*). <b>(e, f)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b> and coronal oblique maximum intensity projection reconstructed image created from postcontrast T1-weighted fat-suppressed images obtained during the portal venous phase <b>(f)</b> show the multiloculated macrocystic mass arising from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body (straight arrow). The thin septa (curved arrow) are well seen on the T2-weighted image and show mild enhancement on the postcontrast image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig15c.jpeg" height="713" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Lymphangioma in a 31-year-old man with sudden onset of left upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a multilocular cystic mass with smooth outer and inner surfaces and multiple smooth tan-white internal septa (*). The cysts are filled with clear yellowish fluid and yellow debris (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the tumor is composed of multiple cysts containing thin eosinophilic fluid (*). The cysts are lined by endothelial cells, and the cyst walls contain small accumulations of lymphocytes. Normal pancreatic tissue is seen in the lower right corner <i>(P)</i>. (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and color Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show different areas of a multilocular cystic mass without internal vascularity in the region of the pancreatic body (*). <b>(e, f)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b> and coronal oblique maximum intensity projection reconstructed image created from postcontrast T1-weighted fat-suppressed images obtained during the portal venous phase <b>(f)</b> show the multiloculated macrocystic mass arising from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body (straight arrow). The thin septa (curved arrow) are well seen on the T2-weighted image and show mild enhancement on the postcontrast image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig15d.jpeg" height="713" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Lymphangioma in a 31-year-old man with sudden onset of left upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a multilocular cystic mass with smooth outer and inner surfaces and multiple smooth tan-white internal septa (*). The cysts are filled with clear yellowish fluid and yellow debris (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the tumor is composed of multiple cysts containing thin eosinophilic fluid (*). The cysts are lined by endothelial cells, and the cyst walls contain small accumulations of lymphocytes. Normal pancreatic tissue is seen in the lower right corner <i>(P)</i>. (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and color Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show different areas of a multilocular cystic mass without internal vascularity in the region of the pancreatic body (*). <b>(e, f)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b> and coronal oblique maximum intensity projection reconstructed image created from postcontrast T1-weighted fat-suppressed images obtained during the portal venous phase <b>(f)</b> show the multiloculated macrocystic mass arising from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body (straight arrow). The thin septa (curved arrow) are well seen on the T2-weighted image and show mild enhancement on the postcontrast image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig15e.jpeg" height="713" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig15e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15e</span>. Lymphangioma in a 31-year-old man with sudden onset of left upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a multilocular cystic mass with smooth outer and inner surfaces and multiple smooth tan-white internal septa (*). The cysts are filled with clear yellowish fluid and yellow debris (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the tumor is composed of multiple cysts containing thin eosinophilic fluid (*). The cysts are lined by endothelial cells, and the cyst walls contain small accumulations of lymphocytes. Normal pancreatic tissue is seen in the lower right corner <i>(P)</i>. (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and color Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show different areas of a multilocular cystic mass without internal vascularity in the region of the pancreatic body (*). <b>(e, f)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b> and coronal oblique maximum intensity projection reconstructed image created from postcontrast T1-weighted fat-suppressed images obtained during the portal venous phase <b>(f)</b> show the multiloculated macrocystic mass arising from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body (straight arrow). The thin septa (curved arrow) are well seen on the T2-weighted image and show mild enhancement on the postcontrast image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig15e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig15f.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig15f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15f</span>. Lymphangioma in a 31-year-old man with sudden onset of left upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a multilocular cystic mass with smooth outer and inner surfaces and multiple smooth tan-white internal septa (*). The cysts are filled with clear yellowish fluid and yellow debris (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the tumor is composed of multiple cysts containing thin eosinophilic fluid (*). The cysts are lined by endothelial cells, and the cyst walls contain small accumulations of lymphocytes. Normal pancreatic tissue is seen in the lower right corner <i>(P)</i>. (Original magnification, ×10; <abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain.) <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and color Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images show different areas of a multilocular cystic mass without internal vascularity in the region of the pancreatic body (*). <b>(e, f)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image <b>(e)</b> and coronal oblique maximum intensity projection reconstructed image created from postcontrast T1-weighted fat-suppressed images obtained during the portal venous phase <b>(f)</b> show the multiloculated macrocystic mass arising from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body (straight arrow). The thin septa (curved arrow) are well seen on the T2-weighted image and show mild enhancement on the postcontrast image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig15f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig16a.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Lymphangioma in a 34-year-old woman with abdominal distention and shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image through the midabdomen shows thin septa (arrow) in a large well-marginated low-attenuation mass, which displaces bowel loops to the right. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique multiplanar reconstruction created from portal venous phase CT shows a large well-marginated predominantly low-attenuation mass with thin internal septa (curved arrow), which extends from the inferior margin of the pancreatic body/tail (straight arrow) and displaces the contents of the left hemiabdomen. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a large (38 × 23 × 9-cm) multiloculated cystic neoplasm covered by a thin clear membrane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150212&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150212/asset/images/large/rg.2016150212.fig16b.jpeg" height="713" width="788" aria-lab